nfronting the Bolsheviks as they sought to promote national security and economic development. He demonstrates the central importance of foreign relations to the political imagination of Soviet leaders, both in their plans for industrialization and in the struggle for supremacy among Lenin's successors. Jacobson adopts a post-Cold War interpretative stance, incorporating glasnost and perestroika-era revelations. He also considers Soviet relations with both Europe and Asia from a global perspective, integrating the two modes of early Soviet foreign relations—revolution and diplomacy—into a coherent discussion. Most significantly, he synthesizes the wealth of information that became available to scholars since the 1960s. The result is a stimulating work of international history that interfaces with the sophisticated existing body of scholarship on early Soviet history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4a20th century. 4aBolsheviks. 4aEurope. 4aEuropean history. 4aSoviet Union. 4aUnion of Soviet Socialist Republics (USSR). 4acivil war. 4ahistory. 4arevolution. 4awar. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  a20th century global history.  a20th century russian history.  abolsheviks.  adiplomacy.  adissolution of the soviet union.  aearly soviet history.  aeconomic development.  afive year plan.  aforeign relations.  aglasnost.  aglobal perspective.  aindustrialization.  ainternational history.  ainternational relations.  alenin.  anational security.  aoctober revolution.  aperestroika.  apolitical imagination.  apolitics.  arevolution.  arussia.  arussian civil war.  arussian history.  asoviet foreign policy.  asoviet leaders.  asoviet union.  athe great turn.  aussr.  aworld politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Ca